<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-891-122  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 891 122.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Nov 13 1989 v217 n21 p9(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber trial powered by network.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Travis, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>North Carolina has its power back after Hurricane Hugo.andP;  RelianceComm/Tec and Alltel are installing a unique fiber-to-the-curbsystem that uses power from the communications network.andP;  Theinitial trial, due to begin in Dec 1989, will provide POTS serviceto 50 homes in an area southeast of Charlotte.andP;  A fiber systemwill be installed on the current copper cables.andP;  The copper wiresthat had carried communications traffic will feed power to the newOCM-6 transmission system and the pedestals, which serve homesusing twisted copper pairs.andP;  Unlike other systems, the OCM-6 usesshorter wavelength optical signals.andP;  The fiber system will costabout 50 percent more to install than a copper system, but bothReliance and Alltel are attempting to reduce costs.andP;  The systemwill probably use power from the customer once the fiber isextended to the home.andP;  Reliance plans to have the system in fullproduction starting sometime in 1990.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Reliance COMM-TEC (communication systems)Alltel Corp. (communication systems).andO;Topic:     Natural DisastersPower SupplyFiber OpticsCommunications EquipmentNorth CarolinaSystem DesignField TestingFiber opticsCables.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Fiber to the pedestal with video overlay. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>